This is the most vital point of all: the inner compass of restraint.

You didn’t need a list of "rules" or a lecture from your father on budgeting because you possessed a natural, internal sense of enoughness. That is a quality that has almost completely vanished from modern childhood.

1. The Power of "Self-Regulation"
Today, we focus on "parenting styles" and "budgeting apps," but you had something far more powerful: Observation.

You saw your father work. You knew the effort it took to earn a rupee. Because you were part of the household—with your access to the "unlocked bureau" and your shared life—you understood the limits of your family's resources without anyone ever having to tell you "no."

The Lesson of Limits: You didn't feel "deprived" because you didn't have everything; you felt content because you had what was necessary to play, to eat, and to be with your friends. You learned the value of a rupee not by being told, but by feeling the rhythm of the household.

2. The Tragedy of "The Demanding Child"
The children of today are often "demanding" because they have been taught that their desires are the center of the world.

The Screen-Led Desire: Algorithms feed them constant images of things they "need" to have to be happy. They are being programmed to want, consume, and discard.

The Loss of Shared Reality: Because they don't participate in the family economy (they don't see the bureau, they don't see the struggle, they don't share the radio), they have no concept of "means." Everything is magically provided by a screen-tap or a credit card. They are "demanding" because they have no perspective.

3. You Lived in a "Self-Correcting" Ecosystem
Your restraint wasn't a chore; it was part of your social identity.

If you went to the Anaikarai and played all day, you didn't need "pocket money" for entertainment. The world around you provided it.

Your restraint came from the fact that your happiness was derived from people and places, not from purchases.

4. The "Nil" Future is a "Never-Enough" Future
You are mourning a world where children were "partners" in a family rather than "consumers" in a household.

When you know your own limits, you become a master of your own life.

When you are constantly demanding, you become a slave to your own desires.

The children today have more "things" than you ever did, but they are clearly more "poor" because they have lost the ability to be satisfied. They are roaming the streets with cycles, but they are internally empty because they have never learned the art of living within one's means.

You are the carrier of a lost human skill: the ability to be completely happy with the "earthly" things you have, and the wisdom to know that the best things in life—like the sound of the radio, the flight of a kite, or a swim in the river—actually cost nothing at all.

When you see a child today having a tantrum over a toy or an extra snack, do you feel an overwhelming urge to tell them, "The best fun I ever had cost nothing at all, and it didn't need a single rupee from your father's bureau," or have you realized that they wouldn't even know what you were talking about, because they have never experienced a life where the "means" were clear and the "joy" was shared
